The paper deals with driver attention prediction in traffic scenes, which involves analyzing visual data and making decisions based on it. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the computer vision (cs.CV) sub-category. Additionally, the paper focuses on human-like driving systems, which suggests that it may also belong to the human-computer interaction (cs.HC) sub-category. The paper also mentions accident detection and prediction, which suggests that it may belong to the robotics (cs.RO) sub-category. The paper proposes a multi-path semantic-guided attentive fusion network, which suggests that it may belong to the artificial intelligence (cs.AI) sub-category. Finally, the paper evaluates its proposed method against state-of-the-art methods, which suggests that it may also belong to the machine learning (cs.LG) sub-category.
